<Review ID>0407717
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 5 GB MP3 Player Green
<Title>Excellent Value!
<Date>Thu Oct 06 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>I've had my player for about a week now, and am very happy with the overall package that Creative has delivered!  I'll be using the player for a number of tasks:     -Rhapsody To Go Subscription (all-you-can-eat download plan)    -Audible.com Subscription    -Ripping my music that isn't available through Rhapsody    -Portable USB hard drive  Some notes/tips: -First thing you need to do is upgrade your firmware from the Creative site.  If you choose the version 2.x firmware, your player will be Windows Plays-For-Sure compliant, and you can use standard software such as Windows Media Player 10 for loading up your software (you must have WinXP SP1 or SP2 to use this firmware).  You'll also be ready to use audible.com for audio books as well.  -If you've read other reviews, you've seen the potential hardware issues such as the headphone jack going bad, or the hard drive crashing.  I'm getting a second player from my vendor as the touchpad is having some issues at the bottom.  So make sure you purchase from a vendor is local or has good return/replacement policy for the first 30 days or so.  -You can buy an extended warranty from Creative directly, as long as you purchased the unit from an authorized reseller.  I think it's a really good insurance policy; for forty dollars you extend the normal warranty (30 days labor, 1 year parts) to 2 years, and all shipping costs are covered.  You can purchase any time within the first 90 days of your original zen purchase.   -Excellent sound from the player.  The ipod has become known for it's great styling, and Creative is known for good sound (remember they're a major vendor for PC sound cards).  -I can create a huge USB flash drive on the Zen when necessary.  On the fly, you can re-partition the device to have a large (up to 4Gb) section as a flash drive.  So in an emergency I can delete songs off the player and have a huge backup disk for my laptop.  -The player is the perfect size to fit in an Altoids mint can.  I had a ton of fun getting a can, lining it with felt, and making my stealth travel cover.  -Rhapsody To Go has been a great service.  For fifteen a month, I can download any of the albums in their catalog (over a million songs to date) to my Zen for portable playing.  So now I can listen to tons of albums from the 70's-80's that have been in a moving box for years whenever I want.  Many of those I only want to listen to once, so why buy the music when I can rent it?  Pretty cool!  -When you purchase, recognize there are two bundles vendors sell.  One has an extra stand-up case and wall charger, the other just has the usb cord for charging.  These extras would cost you around fifty-sixty dollars as add-ons, so make sure you get these included with your initial purchase.  
