<Review ID>6229434
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 5 GB MP3 Player Green
<Title>Controls impossible to operate by feel
<Date>Fri Oct 07 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>I was looking for a mp3 player that I can attach to my belt while walking, working out at the gym, etc and listen to music, audio books, language courses.   I have been using a 512MB Rio Cali, which has been great, but I need more more memory capacity.   The requirements I have are:    1. Attach to belt    2. Easy to use the device and accompanying software.    3. This is a bigee - ability operate the volume, pause/play, rewind  and fast forward quickly and easily with the thing mounted on my belt.  That's because when listening to an audio book, lots of things can cause you to need to rewind a few seconds, or temporarily pause, or change the volume.    4. FM Radio    5. 4 -6 GB    6.  Supports audio book formats  So I got a Zen Micro.   Aside from the fact that one ear of the supplied headphones was dead,  it worked as expected.  I didn't like the supplied software but have previous experience using Windows Media Player so I used that to sync playlists onto the player.  I got a belt clip/case  from dlodirect that works ok.    I had intended to use the bookmark function to keep my place in an audio book when I did something else like listen to music mp3's or FM.  But it is pretty useless for this reason:   If you have a book as a playlist containing many tracks, and are somewhere in the middle, if  you set a bookmark and later return to the book mark,  it does put you back in the track at the right place, but it forgets that you were in a playlist ( so it won't continue on to the next track).  So, ironically, bookmarks are useless for audio books.  Here is a suggestion for designers of mp3 players:   REMEMBER THE LAST POSTION IN EACH PLAYLIST, SO IT WILL RESUME WHERE YOU LAST STOPPED!!  The big problem I ran into was the touchpad control.   After turning the sensitivity to low, I was able to operate it , with some pratice,  as long as I was looking directly at it.   The problem was trying to operate it by feel when it was on my belt, or even when using it in the car,  playing through the car stereo with a cassette adaptor.     The difficulty is that the touch pad is so sensitive, and offers so little tactile guidance that you inevitably accidentally touch the wrong button and screw everything up.     Here's another suggestion for the designers:   Don't try to use the touchpad for everything.  Its ok for scrolling or volume, but for Fwd, Rewind ,  Play/Pause YOU NEED BUTTONS that you can feel in the dark.  So I'm returning mine, and will keep searching, using my Rio in the meantime.   
<Overall>4

