<Review ID>4740141
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 5 GB MP3 Player Green
<Title>The Reviews are Right!
<Date>Fri Sep 16 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>I just got my Creative Zen Micro (in white) a few days ago, and I fall in love with it everyday a little bit more!   When I first saw the box it came in, the "actual size" picture is actually almost ONE inch larger than the real thing! It's that tiny and portable! But not too tiny, naturally.   What I Love about My New Zen Micro (that Creative doesn't tell you): 1. The backlight screen fades from a bright, pretty white into the natural grey after your done selecting the buttons. That's really a nice touch.  2. The Zen Micro came with an extra battery! BUT THAT'S NOT ALL--did you know your Zen Micro can charge while connected to the computer's USB? This is not mentioned in the 3-paged 'instructional manual'! Nor on the 'Quick Tips' paper they give you! The same USB plug is used as a power-charger with the adapter, as well as a regular USB port to the computer--now that's cool.  3. THE ZEN MICRO CAN DISPLAY ASIAN LANGUAGE CHARACTERS! If I had known this, I would've bought the Zen Micro a lot faster! Japanese, Korean, and Chinese are all capable of being displayed on the Zen Micro! I listen to a lot of Korean and Japanese songs, and I hate having to romanize the title names, this is a great feature that should be talked about!   4. The extras! You can't beat this low price! With 1 gigabyte more than the I-pod, the ability to play WMA & WAV, a recorder, an FM radio, and ability to use Windows Media Player 10 to sync your items!   Things that I particularly Don't Like about the Zen Micro:  1. The keypad is too sensitive sometimes, even on the'Low' setting--but I'm getting used to it.  2. The software that comes with it seems redundant, and getting the software updates on the Creative website was a little confusing--I'm still not sure if I've corrected my Creative Media Organizer's freezing problem.  3. If you're going to transfer music in Japanese, Korean and Chinese languages all at the same time, it's best to use Windows Media Player, because the Zen Micro can only display the characters you've selected it to show properly at each start of the Organizer program. Even Zen Media Explorer can only display the default language of your computer's fonts (in my case, Japanese).  4. Simple features like "Play All" are weirdly hidden in a menu called "DJ"--and then you must select "Random Play All." Maybe there's a better way?  5. The instructional manual is brief. VERY BRIEF. In 3 languages, it tells you how to turn on your Zen Micro, get it plugged in and charged up. That's about it. Then Creative included a "Quick Tips" sheet with VITAL INFORMATION about how to use the keypad?! That's not a "Tip"--that's instructional information, and needs to be put inside the manual booklet. I was very disappointed with the poor instructions. Having all of the menus written out in an instructional booklet would've helped me a lot instead of getting frustrated trying to find "Play All."  Overall, the Zen Micro is the best bang for your buck! It sounds great, plays 3 file types of music, displays various fonts and languages, is small/stylish/colorful (even though I got the sleek, sophisticated white!), and full of space for over 2,000 songs with its 5 GIGABYTE memory. Getting an I-pod for any Windows user seems pointless at this point, now doesn't it?!   
<Overall>5

