<Content>Often, I have seen iPods around my school. What can I say? They're popular, and everyone has them. But I'm not everyone, and I didn't want an iPod.   For Christmas, my dad got one of the first few Creative Zen Micros in Canada. He gave it to my mom, and I was immediately intruiged. Not only was I the one who listened to music more often, but I was the one who has had two different MP3 players, and one when they had first come out.   I watched my mom use it with ease. She's new to MP3 players; it was her first. She used it with such ease, whether it was adding music, listening to it, or organizing into playlists.   I immediately wanted one. I finally got one when my birthday came around. I've been using it ever since. I've only had one bad experience with it, and it was quite minor. (It froze for me the other day, and I was honestly shocked. Though, it was easily fixed.)  I don't know whether that other reviewer abused his Zen Micro into taking forever to shut down, but mine certainly shuts down quickly. It takes about 3-5 seconds for it to shut down, and it's not a problem.   Playlists can be made, so there's no problem with separating songs. All songs are put into albums, artists and various other listings. It's even got a very nifty "DJ" feature, that allows you to listen to your most-listened to songs, or your least-listened to songs.   I've been telling all of my friends about the Zen Micro, and they've all said that they want it now, when they used to want the iPod mini. They're both trendy, they're both small, but the Zen Micro has not only a better value, or better colour options, but it's made for everyone; techno geek or newbie.   
