<Review ID>9621998
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 5 GB MP3 Player Green
<Title>WHAT IS WRONG WITH THIS THING?!
<Date>Wed Aug 24 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>I have had a life of crisis with my Mp3 players. First I got a Virgin Player 5GB. Worked for about three months.  So, I got a little Zen Micro. I heard they were pretty good.   Installation wasn't really any major problem. I got it up and running pretty quickly, charged it for about 3 hours, then loaded my songs onto it.  I wasn't really used to the touch pad the Zen Micro has. Anyone who has owned an iPod will be sort of familiar with it. I found it very annoying since I had used a button pad on my Virgin Player.  It took me a long time to get used to the touch pad. About a week, which in my mind is too long to learn to control an Mp3 player.   After about half a month of use, the problems started.  One day I was charging my Micro by hooking it up to my computer via the connection cable. I left it alone for a couple hours. Then I came back and it was making this weird buzzing sound. I looked on the screen and it read, "Hardware problem."   I got a return authorization from Creative so I sent it to them and they sent me a new one.   Again, about half a month later, I saw the words "Hardware problem" on my Zen Micro's screen.  I got ANOTHER return authorization so now I'm on my third one. I was on vacation at the beach and I carelessly went in the ocean with it in my pocket. I know, it was stupid of me, but actually my Zen Micro deserved it.  It was only a couple seconds of being in the ocean when I realized my Zen Micro was in my pocket. I immediately rushed out.  Some Mp3s will work if you get a little water in them. This one was broken for about a month.   One day I tried customer service and got it working again. I was like, "Oh, joy, I got my Zen Micro working again."   By now, I was wanting to smash this thing with a hammer. It was with great hesitation that I decided to use it again.  Just to make sure, I got a THIRD return authorization and they sent me yet another Zen Micro.   Three days later--"Hardware problem."  My fourth return authorization they denied. I guess they got tired of caring for my carelessly made Zen Micro.  Now, the only problem is thinking of a way to destroy the player. Should I fry it? Should I put it in pizza dough and make a pizza? Should I pour gasoline over it and then throw a lit match onto it? I'm not sure, I still haven't decided.  The only joy you will get out of this player is massacring it after the fourth return authorization.   I will never buy another Creative product again.  
<Overall>1

<Review ID>8586401
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 5 GB MP3 Player Green
<Title>Best Value in the Land of Un-iPOD!
<Date>Thu Aug 25 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>The Zen Micro is near perfect.   I bought my Zen Micro last december as a christmas gift to myself, save for a few software issues, I couldn't be happier with my purhcase.   I've owned this player for nine months now and it's been on 5 cross country trips, one trans-atlantic honeymoon, and numerous roadtrips. It's been in my pocket, in my car, and in my bag in 20 inches of snow and 100 degree summers. It's been dropped, shuffled, kicked, and Lumbered. It's still alive, still kicking, and still playing.   I've never owned an Ipod, so this won't be a which one is better review.   All of my files are mp3 or wma, Windows Media Player is my primary music suite, i use it to burn, play, rip, and sync. So starting out i knew i wanted a windows friendly player. The Zen Micro (mine's black) has a lot going for it.   It fits into a hand well, it has a removable battery (this is important), great sound quality, fm stereo, recorder, smooth UI, and a feature that most unipods lack... charm. When it's being used or charged it emits a low pulsating blue light.   It's doesn't have a scroll wheel, but it has a strip! Most people complain about the sensitivity, but it can easily be adjusted for personal preference.   My ONLY complaint is that when i first received it, it was a little buggy. It wouldn't always work seemlessly with WMP and it often required me to restart the frozen micro by taking out the battery and restarting it. over and over again. But after a few firmware releases it's working without a hitch. I've programed WMP to throw a few favorites on there all the time and always put my new music (less than 3 months) on so I can listen to them in the gym.   The accesories that come with the player are great. White earbuds ( i replaced those with some shure headphones, big difference), a case, a stand, a clip (which doesn't really work), and a nice little zen micro bag. Also all the required cables and what not. To me, currently at $218, this player is a best in class. It gives you the most bang for your buck, period.   Creative has been making computer sound equipment for decades and with the zen micro it finally has something with enough quality and, yes, charm to win a nice size of the digital player pie.   Pick your favorite color and buy it.   
<Overall>4

<Review ID>5476300
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 5 GB MP3 Player Green
<Title>Best investment for portable audio ever.....
<Date>Thu Aug 25 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>Purchased not 1 but 2 Creative Zen Micro's for anniversary gifts.  Extremely pleased with the units after we loaded all the necessary firmware and updates to "Plays for Sure" specs.  Took a few tries and eventually called Creative for help.  Customer Service is outstanding - had our problems corrected in minutes.  Had to call Napster for assistance also, their Customer Service was outstanding also, our problems once again were corrected in minutes.  Devices are small, portable, easy to use and sound quality is excellent.  Battery life is good - no strange battery drains or anything.  Units charge up nicely.  Only wish they had as many accessories as I-Pod has (portable speakers, reasonably priced portable items to work with car stereos, etc).  Only problem, hard to find a truly decent sports case for this unit without spending more than $20.00.  Body Glove makes a sports case at $40.00'ish.....  Only bad item is the enclosed belt clip, the clip is not strong enough and the unit slides around whatever it is fastened to.  
<Overall>5

<Review ID>0877646
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 5 GB MP3 Player Green
<Title>I tried it three times... finally gave up
<Date>Thu Aug 25 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>I LOVED my Zen Micro!  It was easy to set up, easy to load and easy to use.  I took it to work everyday for two months.  Then I started having the same problems a lot of people have been talking about- the screen freezing and the buzzing noises. Sent it back to Creative, got a new one right away.  Another two months, another frozen screen and more buzzing.  Sent it back.  Got a new one. Three months. Same thing. Tried it one more time (I really loved that little gadget!) Another two months and the same old song.   Now they want to charge me for a new one!   Argh!   If your Creavtive Zen Micro works, cherish it.  Because there are a lot of malfunctioning ones out there!   
<Overall>1

<Review ID>2885212
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 5 GB MP3 Player Green
<Title>Great Player 
<Date>Fri Aug 26 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>Yes I'm sure you've heard it all before people raving about the Zen Micro but you ignored it right, because it's not an i pod.  Well for those of us who are over the hype and just want to buy a player that works with wma or mp3 music not to mention has a host of other great features, meet your new best friend the Zen Micro.  I have the silver Zen 5 gb and have spent about two weeks with it and I love it!  I have seen that people wrote that the vertical touch pad and touch sensitive controls are impossible or very difficult to use.  It's not impossible but you do need to give it more than five minutes to get used to.  The settings for the touch sensitivy can be adjusted to the preference of each user, I currently have mine set on low and after less than an hour of playing with the controls I felt like a pro.  The one thing that you do want to purchase with Zen Micro is a good set of headphones cause the ones that come in the box are in a word, crap.  Plus, then you can fully appreciate the great sound pumped out by this tiny Mp3 player.  The player fits comfortably in my hand and the vertical touch pad, to me makes more sense than going around in circles.  My favorite feature right now is the DJ: Random play all, so the player takes all the music loaded and plays in random order.  You can also create playlists on the go, which is helpful when you have 800+ songs and just want to hear a select few.  I went from the creative Muvo TX FM 256 to the 5gb Zen micro and the amount of music and features that you can cram into a small package blew me away.  I loved my old player, the problem: I really wanted a player that would hold all my music.  I will say this, that comparing the I pod and the Zen Micro is like comparing apples and oranges, just can't or shouldn't be done.  If you have all your music on iTunes then for you the I pod makes sense.  If you have your music in the wma, mp3 etc formats and use a windows friendly music service then try the Zen Micro.  I really could go on about all the features but the specs are there check them out.  I just really love this player and wanted to share!                
<Overall>5

<Review ID>1872683
<Product Name>Creative Zen Micro 5 GB MP3 Player Green
<Title>A Good "Poor Man's iPod"
<Date>Fri Aug 26 00:00:00 CST 2005
<Content>It actually has a lot more than an iPod Mini, and for less cost.  FM Radio, Voice Recorder, Datebook, it's definitely a nice little item.  The software is really nice, it's easy to use.  I do have a few complaints.  The biggest problem being a high-pitched whine if I ever skip to another song.  It's not really loud, though.  The earbuds aren't that great, besides looking like iPod rip-off buds, they begin to lose sound quality pretty quickly.  Overall, I'd suggest to anyone to buy it.  iPods are just way to commercial, and therefore way too expensive for what you get.  
<Overall>4

